## Business Logic

### Summary of the Account Service

The Account Service is designed to manage user accounts through a set of key business processes, including account management, validation, notification, and error handling. It allows for the creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion of accounts while ensuring that each account is unique and active before any operations are performed. The service communicates with external systems for account validation and utilizes a messaging system to notify other services of account changes. Error handling is implemented to provide meaningful feedback during operations. Stakeholders include account holders, system administrators, external services, and developers, all of whom interact with the service through a RESTful API. The service maintains data consistency by ensuring that related bank information is appropriately managed during account operations.

### Overall API Specification

| Endpoint                | Method | Description                                 | Request Body                        | Responses                                                                                          | Authentication |
|------------------------|--------|---------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------|
| `/accounts`            | GET    | Retrieve all accounts                       | None                                | 200 OK: List of accounts <br> 500 Internal Server Error                                          | No             |
| `/accounts`            | POST   | Create a new account                        | Account object                      | 201 Created: Account created successfully <br> 400 Bad Request: Account with ID already exists    | No             |
| `/accounts/{id}`       | GET    | Retrieve an account by ID                   | None                                | 200 OK: Account retrieved <br> 404 Not Found: Account not found                                   | No             |
| `/accounts/{id}`       | PUT    | Update an account                           | Account object                      | 200 OK: Account updated successfully <br> 404 Not Found: Account not found                        | No             |
| `/accounts/{id}`       | DELETE | Delete an account                           | None                                | 204 No Content: Account deleted successfully <br> 404 Not Found: Account not found                 | No             |

### Endpoints Summary

1. **`/accounts`**
   - **GET**: Retrieve all accounts
   - **POST**: Create a new account

2. **`/accounts/{id}`**
   - **GET**: Retrieve an account by ID
   - **PUT**: Update an account
   - **DELETE**: Delete an account

This structured breakdown provides a clear understanding of the Account Service's functionalities, endpoints, and interactions.

## Plant UML script

Here is a PlantUML sequence diagram script that captures the business logic you provided, including all key actors, interactions, decision points, and endpoints.

```plantuml
@startuml
actor "Account Holder" as AH
actor "System Administrator" as SA
actor "Developer" as D
participant "AccountController" as AC
participant "AccountService" as AS
participant "AccountRepository" as AR
participant "BankRepository" as BR
participant "Feign Client" as FC
participant "Kafka Publisher" as KP
participant "RabbitMQ Publisher" as RP
participant "Error Handler" as EH

== Retrieve All Accounts ==
AH -> AC : GET /accounts
AC -> AS : retrieveAllAccounts()
AS -> AR : findAll()
AR --> AS : List<AccountEntity>
AS --> AC : List<Account>

== Create Account ==
AH -> AC : POST /accounts\n(Account object)
AC -> AS : createAccount(Account)
AS -> FC : validateAccountActive(Account)
FC --> AS : isActive
alt Account is not active
    AS -> EH : handleError("Account not active")
    EH --> AS : BadRequestException
    AS --> AC : 400 Bad Request
else Account is active
    AS -> AR : findById(Account.id)
    alt Account exists
        AS -> EH : handleError("Account with ID already exists")
        EH --> AS : BadRequestException
        AS --> AC : 400 Bad Request
    else Account does not exist
        AS -> AR : save(AccountEntity)
        AR --> AS : AccountEntity saved
        AS -> KP : publishAccountCreated(Account)
        KP --> AS : Message published
        AS --> AC : 201 Created
    end
end

== Retrieve Account by ID ==
AH -> AC : GET /accounts/{id}
AC -> AS : getAccountById(id)
AS -> AR : findById(id)
alt Account found
    AR --> AS : AccountEntity
    AS --> AC : Account
else Account not found
    AS -> EH : handleError("Account not found")
    EH --> AS : ResourceNotFoundException
    AS --> AC : 404 Not Found
end

== Update Account ==
AH -> AC : PUT /accounts/{id}\n(Account object)
AC -> AS : updateAccount(id, Account)
AS -> FC : validateAccountActive(Account)
FC --> AS : isActive
alt Account is not active
    AS -> EH : handleError("Account not active")
    EH --> AS : BadRequestException
    AS --> AC : 400 Bad Request
else Account is active
    AS -> AR : findById(id)
    alt Account exists
        AS -> AR : update(AccountEntity)
        AR --> AS : AccountEntity updated
        AS -> KP : publishAccountUpdated(Account)
        KP --> AS : Message published
        AS --> AC : 200 OK
    else Account not found
        AS -> EH : handleError("Account not found")
        EH --> AS : ResourceNotFoundException
        AS --> AC : 404 Not Found
    end
end

== Delete Account ==
AH -> AC : DELETE /accounts/{id}
AC -> AS : deleteAccount(id)
AS -> AR : findById(id)
alt Account exists
    AS -> AR : delete(id)
    AR --> AS : Account deleted
    AS -> RP : publishAccountDeleted(id)
    RP --> AS : Message published
    AS --> AC : 204 No Content
else Account not found
    AS -> EH : handleError("Account not found")
    EH --> AS : ResourceNotFoundException
    AS --> AC : 404 Not Found
end

@enduml
```

### Explanation:
1. **Actors**: The diagram includes `Account Holder`, `System Administrator`, and `Developer` as actors.
2. **Participants**: The components involved in the service are represented as participants, including `AccountController`, `AccountService`, `AccountRepository`, `BankRepository`, `Feign Client`, `Kafka Publisher`, `RabbitMQ Publisher`, and `Error Handler`.
3. **Interactions**: Each interaction is represented with clear and descriptive messages, indicating the flow of data and operations.
4. **Decision Points**: Critical decision points, such as account validation, existence checks, and error handling, are highlighted using `alt` blocks.
5. **Endpoints**: All the specified endpoints are included in the interactions, ensuring that nothing is missed.

This sequence diagram script should accurately represent the business logic and processes of the Account Service as described.

# API Documentation

## /accounts GET
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: GET  
Authentication: None  
Authorization: None  
Description: Retrieve all accounts.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                |
|----------------|--------|----------|----------------------------|
| None           | -      | No       | No request parameters needed|

### Sample Request
```json
{}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name | Type   | Description                    |
|------------|--------|--------------------------------|
| accounts   | array  | List of account objects        |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dob": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "XYZ123"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountController
- AccountService
- AccountRepository (PostgreSQL)

### Data Mapping
| Source Field | Target Field      | Transformation                |
|--------------|-------------------|-------------------------------|
| -            | accounts[]        | List of AccountEntity objects  |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Internal Server Error",
  "code": 500,
  "message": "An unexpected error occurred while retrieving accounts."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                  | Description                              | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                   |
|-----------------------|------------------------------------------|----------------|--------|--------------------|-------------------------|
| InternalServerError   | General error during processing          | Payload        | string | Mandatory           | Indicates server issue   |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                      | Description                                   |
|-----------|------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
| 500       | Internal Server Error        | An unexpected error occurred.                 |

## /accounts POST
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: POST  
Authentication: None  
Authorization: None  
Description: Create a new account.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                     |
|----------------|--------|----------|---------------------------------|
| account        | object | Yes      | Account object containing details|

### Sample Request
```json
{
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1990-01-01",
  "bankCode": "XYZ123"
}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name | Type   | Description                    |
|------------|--------|--------------------------------|
| id         | string | Unique identifier of the account |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "1"
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountController
- AccountService
- AccountRepository (PostgreSQL)
- BankRepository (MongoDB)
- External Account Validation Service

### Data Mapping
| Source Field | Target Field      | Transformation                |
|--------------|-------------------|-------------------------------|
| account      | AccountEntity     | Converts model to entity      |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Bad Request",
  "code": 400,
  "message": "Account with ID already exists."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                  | Description                              | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                   |
|-----------------------|------------------------------------------|----------------|--------|--------------------|-------------------------|
| BadRequestException    | Thrown when account ID already exists    | Payload        | string | Mandatory           | Indicates duplicate ID   |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                      | Description                                   |
|-----------|------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
| 400       | Bad Request                  | Account with ID already exists.               |


### Response Parameters
| Field Name | Type   | Description                    |
|------------|--------|--------------------------------|
| id         | string | Unique identifier of the account |
| name       | string | Name of the account holder     |
| email      | string | Email address of the account holder |
| accountNumber | string | Account number                |
| accountType | string | Type of account               |
| dob        | string | Date of birth of the account holder |
| bankCode   | string | Bank code associated with the account |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "1",
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1990-01-01",
  "bankCode": "XYZ123"
}
```

### Components Involved

|--------------|-------------------|-------------------------------|
| id           | AccountEntity.id  | Direct mapping                |
